The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                       Drogba banned for 4 matches  Nyon: Union of European Football Associations (Uefa) banned Chelsea striker Didier Drogba for four matches on Wednesday because of his foulmouthed rant at the referee after Chelsea rsquo;s semi-final elimination from the Champions League.  European football rsquo;s governing body also suspended defender Jose Bosingwa for three matches for making offensive comments about Norwegian referee Tom Henning Ovrebo. Chelsea, meanwhile, were ordered to pay euro100,000 (US$138,400) for the improper conduct of its players and fans in that match.  Ronaldo salary  Madrid: Cristiano Ronaldo will earn 13 million euros a year with Real Madrid to become the world rsquo;s highest-paid footballer once the finishing touches are put to his 93 million-euro move from Manchester United, according to a sports daily.   Ronaldo rsquo;s deal would see him move ahead of current soccer salary king, Inter Milan striker Zlatan Ibrahimovic.   EPL opener  London: English Premier League new boys Birmingham City face the toughest possible test on the opening day of next season after being handed a trip to play Manchester United at Old Trafford on August 15. The champions then tackle Burnley the following weekend.   Bhutia affair  Calcutta: IFA secretary Utpal Ganguli had a meeting with Mohun Bagan officials on Wednesday. The club will get back to Ganguli after an executive committee meeting to be held in a couple of days. Meanwhile, East Bengal on Wednesday formed a 10-member core committee to oversee its football affairs during the next season.   Saina advances   New Delhi: Saina Nehwal and Aditi Mutatkar advanced to the women rsquo;s second round in Indonesian Super Series in Jakarta Wednesday. Sixth seed Saina beat Bulgarian Petya Nedelcheva 21-18, 21-12 while Aditi defeated Nicole Grether 21-19, 19-21, 21-7.   
